text:
I like how they used the train as the basis for Joker's development. 
It's reminiscent of ''The Killing Joke'' monologue when Joker was talking to Gordon:


''Memoryâ€™s so treacherous. One moment youâ€™re lost in a carnival of delights, with poignant childhood aromas, the flashing neon of puberty, all that sentimental candy-floss ...

The next, it leads you somewhere you donâ€™t want to go...

...somewhere dark and cold, filled with the damp, ambiguous shapes of things youâ€™d hoped were forgotten..

Memories can be vile, repulsive little brutes. Like children, I suppose. HAHA.

But can we live without them? Memories are what our reason is based upon. If we cannot face them, we deny reason itself!

Although why not? We arenâ€™t contractually tied down to rationality!

There is no sanity clause!

So when you find yourself locked onto an unpleasant train of thought, heading for the places in your past where the screaming is unbearable, remember thereâ€™s always madness!

Madness is the emergency exit...

You can just step outside, and close the door on all those dreadful things that happened. You can lock them away... FOREVER.''

text: What i always love about the stair dance scene is that in other movies a character would usually constantly being shown going down the stairs symbolizing their descent into madness if you will. But here it's the opposite Arthur is shown mainly going up those stairs until now and instead of him feeling sad while he's walking down the stairs he's dancing gleefully without a care in the world and he embraced his descent down the stairs aka his descent into madness. Or maybe it could symbolize a descent into hell and becoming a monster, who knows film is subjective in the long run and i thought this movie was a breath of fresh air for film in a year full of mainly blockbusters and cash grabs and the films that were amazing got shunned by audiences and box office but this didn't even with it's "controversie" (and i'm using that term lightly) which honestly makes me proud cause it just goes to show film as an art form will last for a long time and people will now hopefully give a lot of art house films a watch. Also the memes are great too

text: Joker was the shittiest, most OVERHYPED, OVERRATED film in 2019. Get off the bandwagon sheeple and see it for what it really is, just another ripoff of one of those '70's movies' where the protagonist is a useless, impotent little schmuck who gets screwed by the world and finally 'has enough' then goes completely psycho. It's basically Death Wish, Taxi Driver and others with some Fight Club and American Psycho thrown in i.e. was it all in his head or just some of it? Who cares anyway. The protagonist is utterly detestable and is only 'likable' because everyone else in this fictional world is made to be even worse. He's surrounded by asshole strawman characters who exist only to prop him up and make his 'descent into madness' and psychosis something audiences should empathize with. WELL I DIDN'T. He's a raving psycho and a lunatic and HE'S NOT THE JOKER. Why? The Joker has a sense of humor, no matter how twisted it may be. This guy is just Joachim Phoenix being his usual weirdo self for 2 hours, also that crap he said about letting everyone out of the jails, please. Take away his Oscar and lock this nutcase up for society's own good. This film should be called 'Psycho Clown' or 'Killer Clown' anything but JOKER, it's an insult to a GREAT CHARACTER.

text: Also Iâ€™d like to add that the smile and dance reminds me of the Bjork Stalker and his little last day â€œcelebrationâ€. Right after he mailed the acid bomb to Bjork he filmed himself painting his face and facing around and he had this creepy smile on his face. He was like a child on Christmas. Just like the Stalker, Joker planned to kill himself and that though was such a relief that it was exciting. Maybe even arousing. The only difference is that the Stalker actually blew his brains out (with a .38 caliber revolver) and the joker blew away the man who hurt him so badly. I wonder how much Todd Phillips borrowed from the Stalkers personality to create the Joker? In both I see that same essence of sad and quiet desperation and that glee tinged madness reminiscent of a near demonic entity buried deep down in the human psyche. Chilling stuff really.

text: I think the stairs are a representation of his emotions. Notice how before Arthur became the Joker, he walks the stairs in a slow, tedious and tiresome way, signifying his sadness and depression. text:
That dance was a symbol of freedom for Arthur.
Throughout the movie we only see him going up the stairs, he had the obligation to go to his mother and take care of her even if he wanted her dead. We never saw him going down until this moment.
The moment Arthur was free. Free of medications, his mother.. of everything.
Here he embraces the Joker and not until the last minutes of the movie we see him truly unleashed.
What a beauty of a film indeed.

text:
The end of the afternoon nears. ThereÂ´s no one in the elevator at this time. Outside the sun has begun to set. ThereÂ´s maybe still an hour of light left. The never ending stairs that were so tortuous to walk up are surprinsingly fun to walk down. The rhythm in my veins beats again and I dance my way down those stairs. I feel light as a feather, like I have wings. I jump over the puddles, there are sparks springing from the soles of my shoes and grey pigeons fly off around me as I pass. I laugh. I truly laugh, like IÂ´ve never laughed in my whole life. This is what freedom feels like.
Then suddenly I spot two men at the top of the stairs. Oh no, itÂ´s those detectives.
- Hey, Arthur! We need to talk!
I start running. So do they. I run through the streets of Gotham City, dodging people and jumping over the garbage bags scattered across every sidewalk. I quickly turn around to see them. IÂ´m one block ahead. IÂ´m almost at the subway station. I cross the last avenue when something strikes me. All I know is that my feet are lifted from the ground, the world is turned upside down and my sight is blurred for a moment. I realize IÂ´ve been hit by a taxi. My body hits the windshield and I fall on the asphalt. IÂ´m disorientated but I hear the detectives yelling close to me, I pick myself up and after quickly checking that the gun is still in my pocket I start running again towards the station. I run up three stairs at a time and manage to squeeze myself into the train just as the doors are closing. I catch my breath and notice that the train is full of clowns. TheyÂ´re all wearing masks and some carry signs. Ah, thatÂ´s right. Randall mentioned a protest. Oh no! I thought I had gotten rid of them but I see the detectives entering another wagon. I push my way to the back and cross into another wagon. IÂ´m lucky to go unnoticed amongst this multitude of clowns. ItÂ´s hard for them to spot me. But my makeup is different. I need a mask. I take the mask from one of the clowns standing next to me.
- HEY!
The man pushes me, I dodge him and he ends up beating another guy. A fight starts from which I manage to escape but the detectives get involved in. The subway is a mess and when the doors open at the next stop, the clowns push out the officers and beat them down. Hahahaha. This is fun. For once IÂ´m on the other end of the blade. ItÂ´s not me on the ground getting kicked. I take off the mask and throw it into a dumpster. I donÂ´t need it anymore. I light a smoke and cross the last tunnel that separates me from the studio. Police officers run in the opposite direction, towards the chaos where you can hear screams and a single gun shot. I continue my way.

text: Just saw " Joker ".  I can understand that part of the mind . People who can't or won't be bothered by those who's  lives are much more difficult. With Mental illness.  It's real, there is still a  " Stigma" .Joker  Spirals downward to a place where he can Survive.  Too many grave disappointments.  Lost a Job that he loved Etc...mostly took care of his mother too. Until the end when he discovered the Medical records of his mother and himself.  Father too. I'm only speculating,  but it seemed to me that he strongly believes that his mother didn't try to protect him. Many factors played into this movie.  He was beyond returning to the frame of mind he began. Which was a fragile  point.  There is a lot to said  about the  Human Mind.  I'm not excusing his behavior     however   I can Understand why.  FANTASTIC  ACTOR. Joachim  Phoenix.  He deserved the  Oscar for Best Actor.  I can only hope that people may become more Compassionate for the downtrodden   in our Society.  Thank you.

text:
and ladies gentlemen... you are witnessing one of the greatest scenes of all time in the history of cinema. 

0:01 I love how joker approaches from the side and centers in the camera. blurred image of narrow hallways signifies the undefined pathway/future of joker. Covers the light and becomes darker.
0:18 Love that smirk as the elevator door closes 
0:24 Joker slowly realizes what he is capable of... initially with small body movement then it gets wilder and wilder. All his surrounding is old and seem derelict. But he is new. He is reborn. He is free at last. He is letting go. The burden is reduced as he takes one step at a time. Contrast to climbing up the stairs after work. 

The music is perfect too.. he is ready to rock and roll.

I have always hated Batman and always thought the joker was such a dumb villian, still can't stand heath ledger, still could care less.... Don't get me started on Leto.

text: One of my favorite things in this movie was the stairs. There are multiple times he uses the stairs, whether they be these or the ones at work. A couple of times, most notably at the beginning of the movie, he trudged up the stairs. Life is an uphill battle for him as Arthur. Climbing the stairs every day is an arduous task for him, and heâ€™s grown weary of it. But the day after he kills the Wall Street guys, at work, he seems more at ease and happier, a little more outgoing. He skips down the stairs, and writes on the sign. And here, once he becomes Joker, life isnâ€™t a struggle for him anymore, now that heâ€™s embraced the chaos and tragedy of his life and decides to do whatever he wants. He dances down the stairs to the music in his head, unabashed and unashamed.

text: Its great storytelling. In the beginning of the movie we see Arthur in the toilet dancing very shyly and insecure after he killed those 3 guys. The colors were also much darker, both from his clothes and the camera and the music was sad. Now at the end we see him, dancing in public, with new colorful clothes on, while dancing wildly and free to happy music. That shows us without speaking a word, how much Arthur likes his new role as Joker and that he now finally understands his purpose in life. You could also say that him walking down the stairs, represents him walking down a dark path, full of blood, but he loves this dark path, since everyone hated him when he tried to go the way up. Seriously its great.

text: You know what, I think movies about comic books are lame as fuck in general. The only reason the joker is so good is because it can be seen from a totally comic-free perspective. It's not a good comic movie, it's a great movie with a sad story that could be in any quality drama movie. Now, with that said, I wish they make a joker 2 (of course). The problem is, if they continue to ignore the comic background and make another stand alone movie, it will be weird, like, "why make a joker movie in the 1st place? You can just call it "sad clown" and it'll be ok. I mean, even if comic based movies suck, a joker movie is a comic based movie, albeit losesly. So they have to bring a sequel to a batman universe, otherwise it's just not joker. But, what superhero movie can afford being a part of Arthur Fleck's reality? In other words, it wouldn't be a DC universe joker, but a Joker universe DC movie, if that makes any sense. You need to bring batman in, but it needs to be a completely different batman. A raw, real, authentic guy who doesn't dress in a costume and for some reason is called batman, but is not in any way a silly superhero for kids.

text: Its funny everyone remembers this stair scene but not the one where he was climbing the same stairs when his life was still decaying and he was struggling. Its symbolic, everything with this character is inverse. Comedy are facts but tragedy is comedy to him. Climbing a stairs is normally a symbol of succes or strength and dignity. But in jokers case it was a symbol of failure and depression. The scene stuck out to me, climbing the stairs at night in the rain after a horrible day. And then this scene came, descending the same stairs at daylight feeling better than he ever has before.

text: This is an awesome film about self realization and spiritual awakening. Arthur Fleck is a man who is becoming sane in an insane world. The only killing that I do not approve of is when he kills his co worker. That guy was an asshole anyway but not one deserving of that fate. Killing the three degenerates on the Subway was totally righteous. His mother was understandable and probably a mercy for her and Murray Franklin was a talking head, parasitic modern media brainwashing bastard and those should be killed. But his co worker? No. Yet a part of the process of awakening is learning about free will. I think Arthur has found who he is supposed to be!!! And that is so powerful. If people do not like the proliferation of Joker types in our culture then the way forward is to quit supporting greed, vanity, war, extreme materialism etc. For it makes the unloving culture that creates Arthur Flecks!! This character needed love, a friend, guidance. Instead he got indifference, bullying, hate etc. As he said to Murray Franklin, "ya get what ya fuckin deserve"!!!! Wow!!! So true. Ya got to remember, Arthur does not have a father, a minister, a shaman or a coach to guide him or a loving sibling!!! Sounds like how we get school and mall shooters to me.

text: So. I Was Playing The Video Game Pong. A Classic in And of itself as Well. It Was a Teeth Gnashing Experience of Destinations Unknown. I Felt Like I Traveled From Purgatorio into The Inferno as My Opponent Kept Striking My Heart With Withering Shame. The Competition Between The Enemy of Mine Lasted For Sevyn Weeks. And I Was Growing Tired. Weak. I Felt The Fire Dripping From The Ceiling. It Burned Like Ashes Swept From The Potion of Acid. It Burned. As The Day Before My Freedom From Thus Nightmare Arrived I Opened My Chest. My Soul. The Aura Drifted Asleep as The Acid Crawled into My Heart. It Was Time to Awake From The River of Distortion. And I Defeated The Enemy in One Swift Metaphorical Cut. And I Danced. And Danced. And Danced. And Danced. And Danced. And Danced. And Danced. And . Danced. Even So. amen

text:
Finally saw this yesterday, and yes, Phoenix did a GREAT job.  But, this morning, I watched Rami Malek in Bohemian Rhapsody ajnd thought HE did a great job, too.    yes, by all means, let's KEEP having these awards shows;  they let us see actors as themselves.  BUT,  to say that one actor did a better job in a particular film than another actor did in another film, IS pretty silly.   It's comparing apples and oranges. But, yet, we as humans, can't seem to get away from COMPARING.  If someone does a GREAT job, we can't seem to stop ourselves from pointing out those who did a "not so great" job.   


But, as humans, I don't think our insistence on "comparing" humans will be our downfall.  Our true downfall is our GREED.  But, our insistence on not appreciating "talent"---because we keep insisting OTHERS are MORE talented--- doesn't help.   Our planet will live on without us.  But, the best thing that can happen to the ANIMALS on our planet is that, before they go extinct because of us humans---WE, humans, go extinct.   Humans are the most DESTRUCTIVE species the planet has ever known. So, if you believe in some kind of god, your god really f#cked up in creating humans.

A lot of people say that he becomes Joker by accident and kinda just gets lucky the whole time. This is the scene for me where you can see that he is smart underneath. Heâ€™s off his meds, heâ€™s thinking clearly for the first time. Whilst there is no official illness that Arthur has,  I can believe ADD is partly there. 
Regardless of whether he intended for someone to get shot, he needed a distraction to get away from the cops and he made one. And he did it calmly too. 
Give him time in Arkham alone with his thoughts and heâ€™ll sharpen that mind to near genius level. 
Then Gotham is completely fucked.

Weâ€™re a group thatâ€™s said to have all the â€œbenefitsâ€ which makes us the most suitable targets to discriminate against; because living in a first world country is synonymous with living in heaven to a lot of people. I as a white man watched joker because Iâ€™ve been constantly bullied in my daily life/affairs, and most prominently online for being white, Christian, a westerner. Todayâ€™s society is so clogged up that even bringing up subject matter necessary for further discussion on what we are to do is prone to get you called â€œracist.â€ A â€œNaziâ€ Or a â€œconspiracy theoristâ€ I think joker was a baby step at showing people that society is not always greater than the individual. text: I think that the little smirk when he entered the elevator is him thinking about his final joke. After all, he was going to Murray show, he didn't think about killing Murray, rather he reharshed at his home a sucidie in live telecast of the show. This is his final joke "I hope that my death will make more cents than my life". Eventually it turned out that Murray death made more cents than his life, perhaps this is why Arthur became really amused and really laughed for the first time in his life after he killed him. The Joker has twisted sense of humor.Such a powerful movie. I watched many great ones of all genera,  I had few favorites , untill this one come- this is the best film ever. So sad and realistic. text: This movie is great. DC sucks at making movies imo. They cant ever get it right. But when they do... damn its good. Marvel always "gets it right" but i dont like their movies. they think using comedy will fix the sucky movies. they make it too hollywood and i dont like that. this is just my opinion though. i can see why people like them but theyre too distant from the comics. they make their movies good for the general population but they cant make anything good for actual comic fans. for example, spiderman 1 and 2 with toby maguire, it was much more like the comics than the new ones with tom holland. to tom holland's peter parker, everything is a joke. toby maguires spiderman had the feeling he was actually a super hero who had to sacrafice thing for helping the greater good. newer marvel movies are just there to get money, no interesting story lines. DC also makes bad movies on the regular, like suicide squad, batman v superman, joel shcumacher's batmans, aquaman, etc. but they also have the ability to make really amazing content like the dark knight or joker. my point is newer cbm's are boring and just plain shit.

text: I believe there are parallels to Rocky and this Movie.  In both Rocky and Joker both characters initially find it a struggle to go up the stairs.  Then they go on different paths.  Rocky leaps and bounds to the stop of the staircase.  This symbolizes Rocky conquering life's adversities.  For Joker he's dancing down the staircase.  This symbolizes the Joker gleefully descending into madness. For Rocky he's conquered the staircase, for the Joker he's transcended the staircase.

Heath Ledger made us see a joker that could turn the civilized into puppets. Joaquin Phoenix made us see the joker staring back at us in the mirror. That is the mark of true brilliance. text: I'll explain the deeper meaning of this sequence. After killing several people including his mother, Arthur is now "free",  happy, his makeup flawless, slowly descending (literally) down the steps into madness, when suddenly two cops that represent Arthur's conscience show up and say to him, "Arthur, we need to talk."  Arthur runs away from his conscience as fast as he can but the cops finally catch up to him. Trapped together in a train full of clowns, the cops (conscience) and the clowns battle it out, which represents the inner turmoil inside Arthur. Finally,  the train stops, the doors open, and Joker walks out victorious, the clowns pummel the cops (Arthur's conscience) while Joker laughs and  mocks it. The final shot is of Joker with a single blue tear running down his face representing the death of Arthur as he walks away leaving him behind. The next scene, he's asking Murray to introduce him as Joker.
